SIMPLE: morrow
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Morrow
<hw>Mor"row</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>morwe</ets>,
<ets>morwen</ets>, AS. <ets>morgen</ets>. See <er>Morn</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Morning.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧White as
<xex>morrow's</xex> milk.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We loved he by the <qex>morwe</qex> a sop in wine.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The next following day; the day subsequent to any
day specified or understood.</def> <rj><au>Lev. vii. 16.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till this stormy night is gone,⟦br⟧
And the eternal <qex>morrow</qex> dawn.</q>
<rj><qau>Crashaw.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The day following the present; to-morrow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Good morrow</b></col>, <cd>good morning; -- a form of
salutation.</cd> -- <col><b>To morrow</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>To-morrow</er> in the Vocabulary.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morse</ent>⟦br⟧
